## 1  Objective

The objective of this experiment was to investigate the period of a
physical pendulum made from a uniform bar, and to use the measured period
to determine the rotational inertia of the bar about the pivot and about
its center of mass.

## 2  Theory

For a physical pendulum with total mass \(m\), pivot-to-center-of-mass
distance \(x\), and rotational inertia \(I_\text{pivot}\), the
small-amplitude period is

\[
T = 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{I_\text{pivot}}{mgx}}.
\]

For a uniform bar of length \(L\), the rotational inertia about its center
of mass is

\[
I_\text{cm} = \frac{1}{12}mL^2.
\]

By the parallel-axis theorem,

\[
I_\text{pivot} = I_\text{cm} + mx^2.
\]

Therefore,

\[
T(x) = 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{L^2/12 + x^2}{gx}}.
\]

Differentiating \(T(x)\) gives the minimum-period pivot position

\[
x_\text{min} = \frac{L}{\sqrt{12}}.
\]

## 3  Method

The web experiment modeled the physical pendulum as a PhysX dynamic
uniform bar connected to a kinematic pivot by a horizontal revolute joint.
Gravity was enabled, so the bar oscillated in the vertical plane after it
was displaced by the selected initial angle.  The server recorded the
time, angular displacement, angular velocity, rolling period estimate,
mass, length, and pivot distance during the run.

After the run, Python estimated the period from positive-going zero
crossings of the angular displacement.  The measured period was then used
to infer \(I_\text{pivot}\), and this value was compared with the
geometric value from the parallel-axis theorem.

