## 6  Data and Error Analysis

The measured period was {{ "%.5f"|format(summary.period_measured_s) }} s,
while the small-amplitude theoretical period was
{{ "%.5f"|format(summary.period_theory_s) }} s.  The percent difference
was {{ "%.3f"|format(summary.period_error_pct) }}%.

Using \(I_\text{pivot}=T^2mgx/(4\pi^2)\), the period measurement gives
\(I_\text{pivot}={{ "%.8f"|format(summary.I_pivot_period_kg_m2) }}\)
kg m^2.  The geometric value from the parallel-axis theorem is
{{ "%.8f"|format(summary.I_pivot_geom_kg_m2) }} kg m^2, giving a percent
difference of {{ "%.3f"|format(summary.I_pivot_error_pct) }}%.

The theoretical minimum-period distance is
{{ "%.5f"|format(summary.x_min_theory_m) }} m.  The selected pivot
distance was {{ "%.5f"|format(summary.pivot_distance_m) }} m, differing
from the theoretical minimum by {{ "%.3f"|format(summary.x_vs_xmin_pct) }}%.

The main uncertainty sources are finite telemetry sampling, zero-crossing
interpolation, finite initial amplitude, numerical compliance of the
revolute joint, and any damping in the simulated contact/constraint
solver.

## 7  Conclusion

The result supports the physical-pendulum model.  The measured period is
consistent with the theoretical expression for a uniform bar at small
amplitude, and the rotational inertia inferred from the period is
consistent with the geometric inertia after applying the parallel-axis
theorem.

1. The pivot distance giving the minimum period is \(x=L/\sqrt{12}\).
2. A bar with different mass but the same dimensions has the same
   minimum-period distance because mass cancels from the period formula.
3. The theory is expected to fit best at small amplitude; larger angles
   produce finite-amplitude corrections.

